tial weighte d\nmoving average], right scale)\nWeighted average call rate\nRepo rate\nNet liquidity surplus (+)/deficit (-) (RHS)\nStanding deposit facility rate\nMarginal standing facility rate\nSpread (In absolute terms)\nExponential weighted moving average (RHS)\n-3.0\n-2.5\n-2.0\n-1.5\n-1.0\n-0.5\n0.0\n0.5\n1.0\n1.5\n2.0\n2.5\n3.0\n3.5\n4.0\n4.5\n4.50\n4.75\n5.00\n5.25\n5.50\n5.75\n6.00\n6.25\n6.50\n6.75\n7.00\n7.25\n7.50\n19-Oct-24\n07-Nov-24\n26-Nov-24\n15-Dec-24\n03-Jan-25\n22-Jan-25\n10-Feb-25\n01-Mar-25\n20-Mar-25\n08-Apr-25\n27-Apr-25\n16-May-25\n04-Jun-25\n23-Jun-25\n12-Jul-25\n31-Jul-25\n19-Aug-25\n07-Sep-25\n26-Sep-25\n1\n2\n15\n11\n5\n7\n13\n18\n20\n12\n6 6\n0.00\n0.02\n0.04\n0.06\n0.08\n0.10\n0\n5\n10\n15\n20\nOct-24\nNov-24\nDec-24\nJan-25\nFeb-25\nMar-25\nApr-25\nMay-25\nJun-25\nJul-25\nAug-25\nSep-25'), 0.05445416685883131), (Document(id='rbi_mpr_2025_10_p101_c000', metadata={'report_period': 'October 2025', 'page': 101, 'report_year': 2025, 'report_month': 10, 'report_id': 'rbi_mpr_2025_10', 'page_index': 100, 'chunk_index': 0, 'source_file': 'Oct_2025_RBI_MPR.pdf', 'chunk_id': 'rbi_mpr_2025_10_p101_c000', 'report_type': 'RBI_MPR', 'report_date': '2025-10-01'}, page_content='93\nChapter V External Environment93\npursuing monetary easing to support growth amidst \neasing inflation pressures. \nIn the US, the disinflation process slowed as both \nheadline and core inflation witnessed an uptick in \nQ2 and Q3 with elevated shelter costs. The headline \nCPI and core inflation (y-o-y) rose to 2.9 per cent \nand 3.1 per cent, respectively, in August up from 2.4 \nper cent and 2.8 per cent in March 2025, marking \nthe highest levels since February. The recent uptick \npartly reflects the impact of tariffs and their pass-\nthrough to core components. Inflation, measured by \nthe personal consumption expenditure (PCE) price \nindex — the Federal Reserve’s preferred inflation \nmetric — also witnessed a similar uptick, rising from \n2.4 per cent in March to 2.7 per cent in August (Chart \nV.4a). Core PCE inflation registered an increase from \n2.7 per cent in March to 2.9 per cent in August (Chart \nV.4b). \nIn the UK, headline inflation rose to 3.8 per cent in'), 0.05110669556270209), (Document(id='rbi_mpr_2025_10_p051_c003', metadata={'page_index': 50, 'report_id': 'rbi_mpr_2025_10', 'report_month': 10, 'source_file': 'Oct_2025_RBI_MPR.pdf', 'report_date': '2025-10-01', 'chunk_id': 'rbi_mpr_2025_10_p051_c003', 'page': 51, 'report_type': 'RBI_MPR', 'report_period': 'October 2025', 'chunk_index': 3, 'report_year': 2025}, page_content='Note: Data pertain to 24 States/UTs.\nSource: CAG.\na. Deficit Indicators\n(As per cent of budget estimates)\nb. Revenue and Expenditure\n(Y-o-y growth in per cent)\n81.4\n22.7\n18.9\n0\n15\n30\n45\n60\n75\n90\nRevenue deficit Gross fiscal deficit Primary deficit\n2024-25 2025-26\n5.5\n9.8\n11.5\n-15\n-10\n-5\n0\n5\n10\n15\n20\nRevenue receipts Revenue expenditure Capital expenditure\n2024-25 over 2023-24 2025-26 over 2024-25'), 0.05097410157728677), (Document(id='rbi_mpr_2025_10_p051_c001', metadata={'page_index': 50, 'chunk_id': 'rbi_mpr_2025_10_p051_c001', 'report_month': 10, 'report_year': 2025, 'report_id': 'rbi_mpr_2025_10', 'page': 51, 'source_file': 'Oct_2025_RBI_MPR.pdf', 'report_period': 'October 2025', 'report_type': 'RBI_MPR', 'chunk_index': 1, 'report_date': '2025-10-01'}, page_content='As per the available data for April-July 2025, the key \ndeficit indicators of state governments, as a proportion \nof their budget estimates, were higher compared to \nthe corresponding period of last year, primarily due to \ndeceleration in revenue receipts growth (Chart III.9a). \nThe slowdown in receipts was led by moderation in \nthe growth of state goods and service tax and sales \ntax/Value Added Tax (VAT) collections, even as state \nexcise duties and stamp duties and registration fees \nremained robust. Non-tax revenues increased at a \nslower pace relative to the previous year and grants \nTable III.6: State Government Finances -  \nKey Deficit Indicators\n(Per cent to GDP)\n 2023-24 2024-25 (PA) 2025-26 (BE)\nRevenue deficit 0.3 0.6 0.2\nGross fiscal deficit 2.9 3.3 3.3\nPrimary deficit 1.2 1.7 1.5\nNotes: 1. Data pertain to 31 States/UTs.\n 2. PA: Provisional Accounts; BE: Budget Estimates.\nSources: Budget Documents of State/UTs; and Comptroller and Auditor \nGeneral (CAG) of India.'), 0.05094940352405941), (Document(id='rbi_mpr_2025_10_p103_c001', metadata={'chunk_index': 1, 'page_index': 102, 'source_file': 'Oct_2025_RBI_MPR.pdf', 'page': 103, 'report_date': '2025-10-01', 'report_id': 'rbi_mpr_2025_10', 'chunk_id': 'rbi_mpr_2025_10_p103_c001', 'report_type': 'RBI_MPR', 'report_month': 10, 'report_year': 2025, 'report_period': 'October 2025'}, page_content="targeting by abandoning average inflation targeting \nand de-emphasised the 'shortfall' from the maximum \nemployment.\nThe Bank of England reduced its policy rate by 25 bps \neach in May and August 2025 to support economic \nactivity amidst flagging growth in the second quarter \nand uncertainty surrounding the global trade order \ndespite the successful conclusion of a trade deal with \nthe US. The Bank of England, however, maintained \nstatus quo in September in view of renewed \ninflationary pressures. The European Central Bank \ncontinued with the easing cycle, lowering its key rates \nby 25 bps each in April and June 2025 meetings. In Q3, \nthe bank kept the rates unchanged. The Bank of Japan \nmaintained status quo  over the last five meetings, \nafter hiking by 25 bps in January 2025 (Chart V.6a). \nAmong other AEs, Australia reduced its policy rate in \nMay and August as inflation eased. Canada reduced \nits policy rate by 25 bps in September considering a"), 0.04726880353730001), (Document(id='rbi_mpr_2025_10_p033_c004', metadata={'report_date': '2025-10-01', 'page': 33, 'page_index': 32, 'report_month': 10, 'report_period': 'October 2025', 'chunk_id': 'rbi_mpr_2025_10_p033_c0